STATIC STRIFE

Static electricity can kill silicon chips. Just by walking across a room you
can easily generate several thousand volts of static electricity, which will 
quickly disperse through the nearest convenient conductive object. If you`re
unlucky, this could be your precious Amiga. And while it`s passing through 
your favourite computer, it could be frying your FPU or mashing your memory 
chips.
  The best thing to use is a anti-static wrist strap. We strongly recommend
that you invest in one - they are available at good electronics shops, or 
from any electrical components mail order catalogue. Connect one end to your 
wrist and the other to something large and metal, such as a radiator or filing 
cabinet. This will ensure that any static charge lingering in your body will 
be quickly dispelled.
  If you haven`t got an anti-static strip, there are several simple precautions 
which can help reduce the risk. Before touching your Amiga, touch a nearby 
radiator or other large metal object, which should dispel any lingering 
charge. Don`t forget to also ensure that your Amiga is unplugged before you 
open it, and that you don`t eat or drink near your computer. Few things can 
do a computer more harm than a cup of coffee!


